From: r1mx <r1mx@r1mx>
Subject: [PATCH 3/3] accel/tcg: truncate page[1].addr to target_ulong in mmu_lookup

For cross-page accesses on a 32-bit guest near the top of the address
space, mmu_lookup computes the second-page address as:

    l->page[1].addr = (addr + size - 1) & TARGET_PAGE_MASK

For a 4-byte store at VA=0xFFFFFFFF on a 32-bit guest:

    (0xFFFFFFFF + 3) & TARGET_PAGE_MASK = 0x100000002 & ... = 0x100000000

This 64-bit "overflow" is then used in mmu_lookup1 for a TLB lookup.
The lookup finds the entry for page 0 (same index bits) and computes:

    haddr = 0x100000000 + host_ram_base

which lands 4 GB past the start of guest RAM, outside user virtual
address space, causing SIGSEGV in the subsequent store.

Fix: after size0 has been computed from the pre-truncation value, cast
l->page[1].addr to target_ulong so 0x100000000 wraps to 0x00000000.
size0 must be computed before the truncation.

--- a/accel/tcg/cputlb.c
+++ b/accel/tcg/cputlb.c
@@ -1819,6 +1819,17 @@ static bool mmu_lookup(CPUState *cpu, vaddr addr, MemOpIdx oi,
             l->page[0].size = size0;
 
+            /*
+             * For 32-bit guests, page[1].addr may have overflowed.
+             * Example: addr=0xFFFFFFFF, size=4 gives
+             *   page[1].addr = (0xFFFFFFFF + 3) & mask = 0x100000000
+             * which mmu_lookup1 uses as the TLB lookup key.  It happens
+             * to hit the TLB entry for page 0 (same index bits) and
+             * computes haddr = 0x100000000 + host_ram_base, a bogus
+             * host address that crashes QEMU.
+             * Truncating to target_ulong wraps 0x100000000 to 0x00000000.
+             * size0 must be computed before this truncation.
+             */
+            l->page[1].addr = (target_ulong)l->page[1].addr;
+
             ok = mmu_lookup1(cpu, &l->page[1], mmu_idx, l->type, ra);
